# What is a Database?

Imagine a hospital.

Every patient has a file.

Inside that file are:

* Name
* Age
* Blood Group
* Reports
* Doctor Notes

The hospital stores all of this in an organized way.

A database is simply a **digital filing cabinet**.

---

# Our App's Database

Our app needs to remember:

✅ Users

✅ Blood Reports

✅ Blood Test Values

✅ AI Summaries

✅ Upload Dates

---

# Step 1 – User Information

Every user should have one profile.

Example:

```text
User

----------------------

User ID

Name

Email

Password

Phone Number

Date Joined

----------------------
```

Notice:

We don't need unnecessary details.

Keep the profile simple.

---

# Step 2 – Blood Reports

One user can upload many reports.

Example:

```text
Alice

↓

January Report

↓

March Report

↓

July Report

↓

October Report
```

This is called a **One-to-Many Relationship**.

One user.

Many reports.

---

# Step 3 – Report Information

Each report should contain:

```text
Report

-------------------

Report ID

User ID

Upload Date

PDF Location

Hospital Name

Report Date

AI Summary

-------------------
```

Notice:

The PDF is stored in cloud storage.

The database only stores its location.

---

# Step 4 – Blood Test Values

Each report has many test values.

Example:

```text
Report

↓

Hemoglobin

↓

HbA1c

↓

Vitamin D

↓

WBC

↓

RBC

↓

Platelets
```

Instead of storing everything in one giant block of text, store each test separately.

Example:

```text
Test Name

Hemoglobin

Value

13.2

Unit

g/dL
```

This makes comparisons much easier later.

---

# Step 5 – Why Separate Test Values?

Suppose Alice uploads reports for five years.

If Hemoglobin is stored separately, we can easily create a trend like:

```text
2024 → 11.5

2025 → 12.3

2026 → 13.1
```

That's much harder if everything is stored as plain text.

---

# Step 6 – AI Summary

Every report should also store the explanation.

Example:

```text
AI Summary

--------------------------------

Your hemoglobin is within the
reference range shown on your
report.

Vitamin D is below the
reference range.

--------------------------------
```

Why save it?

Because the user shouldn't have to wait for AI every time they open the report.

---

# Step 7 – Report History

History becomes easy.

Example:

```text
Alice

↓

Jan Report

↓

Mar Report

↓

Jul Report

↓

Oct Report
```

The app simply asks the database:

> "Show me all reports for Alice."

---

# Step 8 – Compare Reports

Since every test value is stored separately:

The app can compare:

```text
Hemoglobin

Jan

11.8

↓

July

13.0
```

No OCR needed.

No AI needed.

Just compare stored values.

---

# Step 9 – Future Features

A good database makes future updates easier.

For example:

Doctor Sharing

```text
Doctor

↓

Can View

↓

Alice Reports
```

Family Accounts

```text
Father

Mother

Child

↓

One Family
```

Notifications

```text
Vitamin D

Low

↓

Send Reminder
```

Good database design supports future growth.

---

# Step 10 – Keep Personal Data Safe

Healthcare data is sensitive.

Your app should:

* Store passwords securely (never as plain text)
* Limit who can access reports
* Encrypt sensitive information where appropriate
* Let users control sharing

Trust is essential for healthcare products.

---

# Our Database Structure

Think of it like this:

```text
USER

↓

REPORT

↓

TEST VALUES

↓

AI SUMMARY
```

Very simple.

Every piece has one job.

---

# Real Example

Imagine Alice uploads a report.

The database stores:

```text
User

Alice

↓

Report

July 2026

↓

Hemoglobin

13.2

↓

HbA1c

5.8

↓

Vitamin D

18

↓

AI Summary

Saved
```

Next month she uploads another report.

The database simply adds another report.

Nothing gets overwritten.

---

# What We Should NEVER Do

❌ Replace old reports

❌ Delete previous values automatically

❌ Store everything in one large text field

❌ Save passwords in plain text

Always preserve the user's history.

